## SQLMap Attack Flow

```
Find URL with GET parameter
         ↓
sqlmap -u <URL> --dbs        → get database names
         ↓
sqlmap -D <db> --tables      → get table names
         ↓
sqlmap -D <db> -T <table> --dump → get data!
```

---

## Lessons Learned

- URLs with GET parameters (e.g. `?cat=1`) are prime SQLi targets
- Always use `--level=5` for deeper scans when basic scan fails
- SQLMap remembers previous results — subsequent commands run faster
- `OR 1=1` is always true — the core of most SQLi bypass attacks
- Single quote `'` is used to break out of the SQL string context
- `-- -` comments out the rest of the query after injection

## Defender's Perspective

- Use **parameterised queries** / prepared statements — never concatenate user input
- Implement **input validation** — whitelist expected input formats
- Deploy a **WAF** (Web Application Firewall) to detect SQLi patterns
- Use **least privilege** database accounts — don't run apps as root DB user
- **Never store plaintext passwords** — hash with bcrypt/argon2
- Enable **database activity monitoring** to detect unusual queries

